<DOC><DOCNO> AP900817-0227 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-90 2214EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Federated-Allied     08-17 0260</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Federated-Allied,0270</SECOND><HEAD>Retailers to Ask More Time for Filing Chapter 11 Plan</HEAD><DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federated Department Stores Inc. and AlliedStores Corp. said Friday they were asking a federal judge for moretime to file a plan for emerging from Chapter 11 bankruptcyreorganization.   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge J. Vincent Aug Jr. is to conduct a hearingSept. 11 on the request to postpone the filing deadline to Feb. 28,1991. Federated and Allied said the extension would allow them toconcentrate on the Christmas retailing season.   It would be the second extension granted by Aug for thecompanies' exclusive right to file a reorganization plan,independent of creditors. Aug on May 10 granted an extensionthrough Sept. 12.   Lawyers for the Cincinnati-based retailers recently told Augthey expected to request a second extension because of thecomplexity and scope of the reorganization effort. Federated andAllied operate 256 department stores in 28 states and employ about100,000 people.   Lewis Rosenbloom, a lawyer for Federated's unsecured creditors,said this week that he expected the companies to request the filingextension.   They filed Chapter 11 reorganization petitions Jan. 15 inCincinnati. The petitions listed $7.7 billion in debt, most of itinherited from when the Toronto-based Campeau Corp. bought Alliedin 1986 and Federated in 1988 in heavily leveraged transactions.   Federated and Allied said they still expect to present theirbusiness plans to creditors in October.   Federated and Allied operate store groups that includeBloomingdale's, Abraham and Straus, Lazarus, Burdines, Rich's,Jordan Marsh, The Bon Marche, Stern's and Maas Brothers.</TEXT></DOC>